The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Nation at a Glance

 Aborted: 5 crore female foetuses 

 Gurgaon (PTI): Around five crore female foetuses in the country were terminated last year, Haryana health minister Kartar Devi said on Sunday.

 Devi, who was speaking at the inauguration of a clinic in the civil hospital, said said the situation was sad and unfortunate.

 he health minister noted that the sex ratio in the state was very alarming. She said: We must not consider girls as a burden on the family. 

 Citing the example of Indira Gandhi, she added that girls can bring honour to their families. 

 Devi announced that the Haryana government intended to reduce the maternal mortality ratio from the current 300 in a lakh mothers to below 100 by 2010.

 Axe on beggar doctor

Ghaziabad/New Delhi (PTI): The Uttar Pradesh government has 

decided to suspend Ajay Agarwal, one of the two doctors from the state named in 

a sting operation for allegedly agreeing to amputate the limbs of people to make 

them beggars. 

 Another doctor has been questioned by Delhi police. 

 Agarwal had been untraceable since a television channel aired the expose on Saturday. 

 Sanjeev Malik, the outgoing president of the Indian Medical Association, said the three doctors memberships would be revoked. He described their alleged actions as barbarous. 

 NRI body

 Phagwara (PTI): The body of an NRI who had been missing 

for the past six days was found on Sunday in Hoshiarpur district.

 UK-based millionaire Banta Sahota was in his seventies. Police have booked his brothers grandson, Vikas, 24, under Section 364 (kidnapping or abducting in order to murder) of the Indian Penal Code.

 Seer security

 Bhubaneswar (PTI): The Orissa unit of the BJP demanded on 

Sunday that the security of the Puri sankaracharya, Swami Nischalananda Saraswati, 

be tightened in the wake of the bomb explosion near his mutt on Saturday. The 

party also demanded an inquiry into the blast.

 Lok adalats

New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court has dismissed a PIL saying 

permanent lok adalats should be set up in all government departments and public 

sector industries.

 Power distribution companies in Delhi will be protected by the Central Industrial Security Force from July 31 to check widespread electricity pilferage, a major reason for revenue loss.




